the purpose of the present study was to verify whether zinc
consumption as a nutritional supplement would be a clinic-
ally beneficial complementary treatment to improve func-
tional outcomes in subjects with ADHD.
Methods
Search strategy and study selection
The Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and
Meta-Analyses (PRISMA) protocol was followed for design,
performance, and reporting of this meta-analysis (Picot et al.
2012). A literature and comprehensive search through PubMed,
Scopus, ISI web of science, and Google Scholar databases was
carried out using the following search terms: (“zinc” OR “zn”
OR “zinc supplementation” OR “zinc supplement” OR “oral
zinc supplementation”) AND (“Attention deficit hyperactivity
disorder” OR “attention deficit disorder with hyperactivity” OR
“Attention
deficit
disorder”
OR
"Attention
Deficit
and
Disruptive Behavior Disorders" OR “ADHD” OR “inattention”
OR “impulsivity” OR “hyperactivity” OR “minimal brain dys-
function” OR “attention deficit” OR “disruptive behavior disor-
der”
OR
“Impulsive
Behavior”
OR
“hyperkinesia”
OR
“Conners
scale”)
AND
(“randomized
controlled
trial”
OR “clinical trial” OR “randomized” OR “placebo” OR
“intervention studies” OR “intervention” OR “controlled trial”
OR “random” OR “randomly” OR “blind” OR “RCT” OR
“trial”) (Supplementary Table 1). Our search was conducted up
to January 13, 2021, with no restrictions in publication time or
language. Besides, the reference lists of selected papers were
manually checked to identify further relevant trials.
The process of selecting relevant studies was performed
based on the PICOS (population/intervention/comparison/
outcome/study design) framework: P (children with a diag-
nosis of ADHD), I (oral zinc supplementation), C (control
group received placebo), O (clinical symptoms of ADHD), S
(parallel or cross-over clinical trial).
Inclusion and exclusion criteria
Studies were selected if they met the following criteria: (1)
original randomized-controlled clinical trial with either par-
allel or cross-over design; (2) performed on school-aged
children with a diagnosis of ADHD; (3) examined the effect
of oral zinc supplementation on ADHD symptoms with a
control group; (4) reported sufficient data on clinical symp-
toms of ADHD through validated scales in both treatment
and control groups. We excluded studies in this systematic
review and meta-analysis if they: (1) were trials without a
control group; (2) used zinc in combination with other
nutrients; (3) were observational studies, animal models,
conference papers, letters, editorial, reviews, or case reports.
Quality assessment and data extraction
The Cochrane Collaboration’s tool (Higgins et al. 2011) was
applied to evaluate the quality of eligible studies by two
independent researchers. This validated checklist contains
seven domains involving selection bias (random sequence
generation
and
allocation
concealment),
reporting
bias
(selective reporting), other sources of bias, performance bias
(blinding participants and personnel), detection bias (blind-
ing outcome assessment), and attrition bias (incomplete out-
come data). Each domain was scored as low risk of bias,
high risk of bias, and unclear risk of bias.
The following required information for the current sys-
tematic review and meta-analysis was extracted separately by
two reviewers (HM and ST): First author, country, publica-
tion year, study design, ADHD diagnostic criteria, gender
and mean age of subjects, sample size (intervention and
control groups), duration of intervention, zinc dose, basic
medicine, measurement scale of ADHD clinical symptoms,
as well as mean changes and their standard deviations (SDs)
of outcomes.
Statistical analysis
To analyze the effects of zinc supplementation on ADHD
symptoms, standardized mean difference (SMD) with a 95%
confidence
interval
(CI)
were
pooled
using
Hedges’s
adjusted g method. Mean change and standard deviation
(SD) of ADHD symptoms in intervention and control
groups were carried out to obtain the overall effect size for
each outcome. If the studies did not report SD changes
(Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004; Arnold et
al. 2011; Noorazar et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora et
al. 2011), we used the following suitable formula: SD2 ¼
[(SD baseline
2þSD final
2)  (2  R  SD baseline  SD
final)], considering the correlation coefficient (R) of 0.5
(Borenstein et al. 2011). All analyses for ADHD clinical
symptoms were repeated using correlation coefficients of 0.2
and 0.8 to approve that our results were not sensitive to the
chosen correlation coefficient (R ¼ 0.5). Furthermore, SD
was computed by relevant formulas in studies that presented
standard errors (SEs), 95% confidence intervals, and inter-
quartile ranges (Hozo, Djulbegovic, and Hozo 2005). We
used a random-effects model to calculate the pooled effect
size for all outcomes because data were derived from publi-
cations, and studies have come from different settings.
Heterogeneity across the studies was explored by the I2 stat-
istic, described as I2 values > 50% or p < 0.05 (Higgins et al.
2003). To detect probable sources of heterogeneity, subgroup
analyses were conducted according to the duration of the
intervention (<8 weeks vs 8 weeks), the dosage of oral zinc
supplementation (>20 mg/d vs <20 mg/d), basic medication
(methylphenidate consumption vs no medication), ADHD
measurement scale (Conners’ scale vs non-Conners’ scale)
and sample size (60 vs <60). We also executed fractional
polynomials modeling to examine the non-linear potential
effects
of
zinc
dosage
(mg/d)
and
treatment
duration
(weeks) on ADHD total scores. The proportion of every sin-
gle study on the overall effect was checked through sensitiv-
ity analyses. Egger’s regression test and Begg’s test method
evaluated the possibility of publication bias. Statistical ana-
lysis was performed using STATA version 14 software (Stata
Corp, College Station, Texas, USA). The certainty of the
