Results
Literature search
Out of 254 publications yielded from all electronic data-
bases, 83 records were excluded because of duplicates, ani-
mal studies, and non-original articles. Then, after removing
155 records by screening the title and abstract, 16 papers
were remained for reading the full text. In the next step, 10
studies were excluded based on the following reasons: con-
ducted on healthy children (n ¼ 3), administered zinc in
combination with other nutrients (n ¼ 3), studies without a
control group (n ¼ 1), and studies that had observational
design (n ¼ 3) (Supplementary Table 2). Eventually, 6 trials
met the eligibility criteria (Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and
Khademi 2004; Arnold et al. 2011; Bilici et al. 2004;
Noorazar et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora et al. 2011).
The flow chart for the study selection process is illustrated
in Figure 1.
Findings from the systematic review
Study characteristics
In summary, out of six studies enrolled a total of 489
school-aged children with a diagnosis of ADHD (245 sub-
jects in the zinc group and 244 subjects in the control
group) in both gender with age ranged from 7 to 10 years
old. These clinical trials were published from 2004 to 2020
and were conducted in Iran (Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi,
and Khademi 2004; Noorazar et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016),
Chili (Zamora et al. 2011), USA (Arnold et al. 2011), and
Turkey (Bilici et al. 2004). The design of all selected studies
was parallel and double-blind. A daily dose of zinc supple-
mentation differed from 10 mg (Noorazar et al. 2020;
Zamora et al. 2011) to 40 mg (Bilici et al. 2004). The dur-
ation of the intervention among studies was varied between
6 weeks (Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004;
Noorazar et al. 2020; Zamora et al. 2011) to 12 weeks (Bilici
et al. 2004). In four studies, zinc supplementation was used
as
an
adjunct
to
methylphenidate
(Akhondzadeh,
Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004; Noorazar et al. 2020;
Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora et al. 2011), while the other two
studies received zinc supplementation alone (Arnold et al.
2011; Bilici et al. 2004). Among the eligible records, various
scales were used to measure ADHD symptoms including the
Conners scale (Arnold et al. 2011; Bilici et al. 2004;
Noorazar et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora et al. 2011),
Swanson, Nolan, and Pelham rating (SNAP) (Arnold et al.
2011), and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder scale
(ADHDS) (Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004;
Bilici et al. 2004), according to reports from parents
(Noorazar et al. 2020), teachers (Bilici et al. 2004), or both
(Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004; Arnold et
al. 2011; Bilici et al. 2004; Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora et al.
