total score (Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004;
Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora et al. 2011). A description of the
characteristics of included trials is summarized in Table 1.
Risk of bias assessment
All selected studies were categorized as good quality. Also,
all included studies reported enough information about ran-
dom sequence generation and blinding of participants.
Nevertheless, only one trial properly presented the proced-
ure
of
blinding
outcome
assessment
(Akhondzadeh,
Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004). Furthermore, three stud-
ies had a low risk of bias regarding allocation concealment
(Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004; Noorazar
et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016) and selective outcome report-
ing (Arnold et al. 2011; Bilici et al. 2004; Noorazar et al.
2020). The item was related to the other sources of bias
included in the statistical analysis adjusted for baseline val-
ues
described
in
four
publications
(Akhondzadeh,
Mohammadi,
and
Khademi
2004;
Arnold
et
al.
2011;
Noorazar et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016). In addition, most
studies had mentioned the process of incomplete outcome
data except for one trial (Bilici et al. 2004). The results of
the risk of bias assessment using the Cochrane collaboration
tool are provided in Table 2.
Findings from the meta-analysis
Effect of zinc supplementation on ADHD total scores
The pooled results from 6 clinical trials (Akhondzadeh,
Mohammadi, and Khademi 2004; Arnold et al. 2011; Bilici
et al. 2004; Noorazar et al. 2020; Salehi et al. 2016; Zamora
et al. 2011) showed that zinc supplementation significantly
reduced ADHD total scores compared to the placebo (SMD:
0.62 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 1.24 to 0.002, p ¼ 0.04) in
children with ADHD. However, heterogeneity among studies
was significant (I2 ¼ 89.9%, p < 0.001) (Figure 2). Therefore,
heterogeneity was attenuated by subgroup analysis based on
ADHD measurement scale (I2 < 50%) with significant
between
subgroup
heterogeneity
(p < 0.001).
Moreover,
Findings from the subgroup analysis showed that zinc sup-
plementation had a favorable effect on ADHD total scores
in trials that used non-Conners’ scale (SMD: 1.53 Hedges’
g; 95% CI: 1.85 to 1.20, p < 0.001). We also observed a
greater reduction in ADHD total scores when children
received zinc supplementation with methylphenidate (SMD:
0.50 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 0.96 to 0.03, p ¼ 0.03). Further
subgroup analysis according to duration, dose, and the sam-
ple size is stated in Table 3. The result of sensitivity analysis
revealed the exclusion of Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and
Khademi (2004) study (Akhondzadeh, Mohammadi, and
Khademi 2004) (SMD: 0.50 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 1.21 to
0.20), Bilici et al. (2004) study (Bilici et al. 2004) (SMD:
0.38 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 0.79 to 0.02), Salehi (2016)
study (Salehi et al. 2016) (SMD: 0.64 Hedges’ g; 95% CI:
1.42 to 0.12), and Zamora (2011) study (Zamora et al.
2011) (SMD: 0.65 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 1.36 to 0.06)
changed pooled effect size (CI range: 1.42, 0.20). No evi-
dence of publication bias based on Begg’s test (p ¼ 1.00),
and Egger’s test (p ¼ 0.23) was found.
Following non-linear dose-response, the relation between
the zinc dosage and ADHD total score did not statistically
significant (Pnon-linearity ¼ 0.18). Regarding Figure 3A, it
sounds that with increasing zinc dosage, we observed a
greater reduction in the ADHD total score, whereas the
reducing effect of zinc supplementation at the dosage of
approximately < 22 mg/d was more rapid. Moreover, there
was no significant non-linear relation between duration and
ADHD total score (p non-linearity ¼ 0.64). So that, the highest
decrease occurred in a longer duration (Figure 3B).
Effect of zinc supplementation on hyperactivity scores
The pooled mean difference of 3 studies (Arnold et al. 2011;
Bilici et al. 2004; Noorazar et al. 2020) based on the ran-
dom-effects
