reduction in hyperactivity scores after zinc supplementation
(SMD: 0.93 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 3.31 to 1.45, p ¼ 0.44).
However, significant heterogeneity was detected between the
studies (I2 ¼ 98.6%, p < 0.001) (Figure 4). Sensitivity ana-
lysis showed that the exclusion of any study did not alter
the overall effect (CI range: 4.88, 1.91). The Begg’s test
(p ¼ 1.00), and Egger’s test (p ¼ 0.19) showed no publica-
tion bias.
Effect of zinc supplementation on inattention scores
Overall, 3 effect sizes (Arnold et al. 2011; Bilici et al. 2004;
Noorazar et al. 2020) including 305 children with ADHD
were evaluated in the random-effects model. We found that
zinc supplementation had not a significant effect on inatten-
tion scores (SMD: 0.21 Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 0.09 to 0.51,
p ¼ 0.17) with low heterogeneity (I2 ¼ 34.4%, p ¼ 0.21)
(Figure
5).
Exclusion
of
Noorazar
(2020)
(SMD:
0.34
Hedges’ g; 95% CI: 0.08 to 0.59) from the analysis changed
the overall effect (CI range: 0.40, 0.63). The results of
Begg’s test (p ¼ 1.00), and Egger’s test (p ¼ 0.58) explained
no publication bias.
Grading the evidence
The GRADE approach was applied to evaluate the certainty
of the evidence (Supplementary Table 3). The evidence was
rated moderate and very low quality for ADHD total scores,
inattention scores, and hyperactivity scores, respectively. The
evidence was downgraded for serious inconsistency and
imprecision.
Discussion
ADHD has a negative impact on many major life activities
and places a substantial economic burden on families and
health care services (Barkley 2020). Deficiency of zinc, as
well as sufficient zinc supply, has been suggested to con-
tribute to the increased risk and improvement of ADHD
symptoms,
respectively
(Dodig-Curkovic
et
al.
2009;
Hambidge and Krebs 2007). Zinc contributes to the brain
