CRITICAL REVIEWS IN FOOD SCIENCE AND NUTRITION
7
This meta-analysis is the first to investigate the effects of
zinc supplementation on ADHD total scores, hyperactivity
scores, and inattention scores among patients with ADHD.
We summarized all of the available evidence which showed
that zinc supplementation significantly reduces ADHD total
scores. The test for subgroup differences showed that there
are statistically significant subgroup effects, suggesting that
ADHD measurement scale and basic medication modify the
effect of zinc supplementation on the ADHD total scores
such a way that non-Conners’ scale and zinc supplementa-
tion with methylphenidate therapy had a more lowering
effect. However, the covariate distribution is concerning for
current subgroup analysis. The dose-response analysis indi-
cated a non-significant linear association between ADHD
total score with zinc dosage as well as study duration. Also,
zinc supplementation results did not significantly affect the
hyperactivity scores and inattention scores. Given the impact
of sensitivity analysis on our final results, deriving findings
should be interpreted with caution.
Several mechanisms are known that could explain the
effects of zinc supplementation on ADHD symptoms. Zinc
level is highest in the brain compared to other organs and
its homeostasis is tightly regulated (Portbury and Adlard
2017). It contributes to the efficient synaptic transmission,
metabolism of neurotransmitters, structural component of
about 70% of proteins, function of over 2000 regulatory
proteins and transcription factors and also 300 enzymes
(Portbury and Adlard 2017). So, given the critical role of
zinc in brain, zinc deficiency might result in pathological
conditions such as ADHD. Dopamine and melatonin have
important roles in the pathophysiology of ADHD. This
neurodevelopmental disorder is associated with low dopa-
mine levels in certain brain areas (Bijlenga et al. 2019). On
the other hand, melatonin, the hormone produced by the
pineal gland, regulates dopaminergic system. Melatonin
production is regulated by zinc, so zinc deficiency can be
assumed as ADHD pathophysiology (Dodig-Curkovic et al.
2009). Another possible explanation is that zinc deficiency
leads to dysfunction of enzyme delta-6 desaturase leading
to the altered anabolism of essential long-chain fatty acids,
which then disrupts the constituting neuronal membrane
causing ADHD pathophysiology (Dodig-Curkovic et al.
Figure 4. Forest plot of the effect of zinc supplementation on hyperactivity scores using a random-effects model. SMD: standardized mean difference, CI: confi-
dence interval.
Figure 5. Forest plot of the effect of zinc supplementation on inattention scores using random effects model. SMD: standardized mean difference, CI: confi-
dence interval.
8
S. TALEBI ET AL.
2009). So, zinc supplementation may have a great benefit
for ADHD.
Despite the interesting results of the present meta-ana-
lysis, some limitations should be considered. ADHD is a
heterogeneous disorder with variation in etiology and patho-
physiology. So in the ADHD studies, potentially, the residual
confounding could be high. Furthermore, other confounding
factors including socio-economic factors, nutrition, and gen-
etics background, inter and intra-individual differences, and
rate of zinc deficiency could not be considered. Another
major limitation is the insufficient number of included stud-
ies in this meta-analysis.
On the other hand, there are several strengths which
should not be omitted. We have to note that this is the first
meta-analysis evaluating the effects of zinc supplementation
on ADHD. Another strength of this study is subgroup ana-
lysis and using the GRADE scoring system to evaluate the
quality of the overall evidence. We also designed a dose-
response meta-analysis to have a more complete picture of
the effects of zinc supplementation on ADHD total scores as
well easier interpretation of results based on the totality of
available evidence. In addition, we tried attempted to limit
bias by following the PRISMA guidelines.
Implications for practice
The evidence from this meta-analysis suggests that zinc sup-
plementation can significantly reduce ADHD total scores.
However, most trials were conducted in Asian populations
with moderate to high risk of zinc deficiency, so transfer-
ability of these findings might not be possible to other
populations with different characteristics. Also due to multi-
factors contributing to ADHD (Posner 2020), and diagnostic
unreliability, specifically in young children (Dodig-Curkovic
et al. 2009), these results should be interpreted with caution.
Furthermore, other aspects in a zinc supplementation pro-
gram in ADHD patients such as differences in absorption,
metabolism and bioavailability of zinc (Dodig-Curkovic et
al. 2009), age, individual variations, maternal and family
functioning and responsivity (Black 1998), maternal life style
during pregnancy (Dodig-Curkovic et al. 2009), psychosocial
and developmental stimulation, environmental stress and
socio-economic context should be considered for successful
zinc supplementation planning (Black 1998).
Conclusion
The evidence from this meta-analysis suggests that zinc sup-
plementation can significantly reduce ADHD total scores.
The certainty of the evidence was graded moderate to very
low for all outcomes. However, we could not draw a defini-
tive conclusion due to the insufficient numbers of included
studies in this meta-analysis. Future well-designed, large-
scale randomized controlled trials with sufficient control for
confounding are needed to establish the benefit of zinc sup-
plementation for ADHD.
Author contribution
S.T and H.M contributed to the conception of research, searched data-
bases, data extraction, and performed the statistical analysis. S.T, A.Gh,
and M.M wrote the manuscript. H.M critically revised the manuscript.
All authors approved the final manuscript for submission.
